---
// Reliability section: durable execution, exactly-once, residency
const properties = [
  {
    title: 'Crash recovery',
    body: 'Every turn commits atomically to a durable event log. On worker death, another worker restores from the last committed turn and continues. O(1) resume from the latest snapshot.',
    shipped: true,
  },
  {
    title: 'Exactly-once tools',
    body: 'Each tool call gets a deterministic idempotency key from (run_id, segment, step). On resume the runtime skips already-completed side effects. Paying twice after a crash is not a failure mode.',
    shipped: true,
  },
  {
    title: 'Budget caps and loop detection',
    body: 'Per-run and per-tenant cost ceilings are engine-enforced, not suggestions. Reflection loops are detected and halted before they cross the cap.',
    shipped: true,
  },
  {
    title: 'Durable waits on provider outage',
    body: 'When a model provider returns 429 or goes down, the run parks as a durable wait with backoff rather than failing. It resumes automatically on recovery, freeing the worker in the meantime.',
    shipped: true,
  },
  {
    title: 'Residency by design',
    body: 'Run state and payloads stay in the region where the agent was dispatched. Only content hashes travel for the global audit index. Residency requirements are a first-class design property, not an afterthought.',
    shipped: true,
  },
  {
    title: 'Determinism contract',
    body: 'The boundary between recorded outputs (model responses, tool results, time, randomness) and deterministic orchestration is explicit and tested. Replay-based regression lets you diff a run against a new model or prompt with a deterministic test.',
    shipped: false,
    note: 'Replay-based regression is in the v1 build.',
  },
];
---

<section id="reliability" class="reliability">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-label">Reliability</p>
    <h2>Built for production failures, not just sunny paths.</h2>
    <p class="rel-intro">
      Model calls are hundreds of milliseconds. Durable turn commits are
      sub-millisecond. Per-step durability and governance cost essentially
      nothing against model latency.
    </p>

    <div class="rel-grid">
      {properties.map(p => (
        <div class="rel-card">
          <div class="rel-card-head">
            <h3>{p.title}</h3>
            {p.shipped
              ? <span class="rel-tag rel-tag-live">shipped</span>
              : <span class="rel-tag rel-tag-build">in progress</span>
            }
          </div>
          <p>{p.body}</p>
          {p.note && <p class="rel-note">{p.note}</p>}
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<style>
  .reliability {
    background: var(--bg-alt);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
  }
  .rel-intro {
    color: var(--text-secondary);
    max-width: 600px;
    margin-top: 16px;
    margin-bottom: 48px;
  }
  .rel-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
    gap: 20px;
  }
  .rel-card {
    background: var(--surface);
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 8px;
    padding: 24px;
  }
  .rel-card-head {
    display: flex;
    align-items: flex-start;
    justify-content: space-between;
    gap: 8px;
    margin-bottom: 10px;
  }
  .rel-card p {
    font-size: 0.875rem;
    color: var(--text-secondary);
    line-height: 1.65;
  }
  .rel-tag {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.65rem;
    padding: 2px 8px;
    border-radius: 20px;
    white-space: nowrap;
    flex-shrink: 0;
    margin-top: 2px;
  }
  .rel-tag-live  { background: rgba(45,125,70,0.12);  color: var(--success); }
  .rel-tag-build { background: rgba(180,83,9,0.10);   color: var(--warning); }
  .rel-note {
    margin-top: 8px;
    font-size: 0.78rem !important;
    color: var(--text-muted) !important;
    font-style: italic;
  }

  @media (max-width: 900px) {
    .rel-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; }
  }
  @media (max-width: 600px) {
    .rel-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
  }
</style>
